(click to hear the word) (tr-rzm)<br>
n. <br>
The unlawful use or threatened use of force or violence by a person or an organized group against people or property with the intention of intimidating or coercing societies or governments, often for ideological or political reasons. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
&quot;unlawful&quot;<br>
<br>
That's the problem.  The logic in the definition of terrorism is pretty circular.  <br>
<br>
Basically, terrorism can never be perpetrated (sp) by the group in power, because they define what is or is not lawful.  The group in power can use terror as a means of keeping the other group fearful, but it's not actually terrorism because they're not trying to enact change (usually when the group in power does it they're trying to prevent a change of some kind or another by scaring the other group from rebellion).<br>
<br>
Because the actions the US and others took in Afghanistan were basically deemed lawful by the world community, it's not terrorism (as it is defined), even if everything else in the definition matches.<br>
<br>
I'll be frank... terrorism is a tool.  It is a weapon by which the weak can fight against the strong.  Whether their cause is just or not depends on the circumstances.  Our &quot;British Tea Party&quot; during revolutionary times <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>completely</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> fits the definition of &quot;terrorism&quot; but it is celebrated as a part of our American history &amp; heritage.<br>
<br>
I don't say that to justify Sept 11th, I just accept that terrorism is a useful tool in both history and modern times.  It will always be a problem for those in power, and the more enemies they make the more problems they'll have with it.  The people who do it aren't more or less cowardly then anyone else, they're just usually in circumstances where they have so little power that lashing out at civilians or property is the only way to inflict damage on their enemies and/or get their voice heard.<br>
<br>
- Syllestrae <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xenojones>XENOJONES</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1353<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/1/03 2:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=538.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: who's the terrorist?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'll be frank... terrorism is a tool. It is a weapon by which the weak can fight against the strong. Whether their cause is just or not depends on the circumstances. Our &quot;British Tea Party&quot; during revolutionary times completely fits the definition of &quot;terrorism&quot; but it is celebrated as a part of our American history &amp; heritage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
